# Odin runtime model

Odin has no exceptions, no garbage collector, and no hidden allocations. Memory
and errors are explicit and travel as ordinary values; the one piece of implicit
machinery is `context`. This is the companion to the grammar in @odin/lang.

## The context

Every proc using the default `"odin"` calling convention silently carries a
`context` — a per-scope record holding `context.allocator`,
`context.temp_allocator`, `context.logger`, `context.user_ptr`, and more.
`make`, `new`, `append`, and `delete` use `context.allocator` implicitly. Swap
it for a scope just by assigning:

```odin
context.allocator = my_arena_allocator   // scoped to the enclosing block
buf := make([]u8, 1024)                   // now allocated from the arena
```

`"contextless"` and `"c"` convention procs do **not** carry a context.

## Allocators

Allocators are first-class values. The standard ones:

| Allocator | Use |
|-----------|-----|
| default heap | general-purpose (the initial `context.allocator`) |
| `mem.Arena` / `virtual.Arena` | bump-allocate, free everything at once |
| `context.temp_allocator` | scratch memory; reclaim with `free_all(context.temp_allocator)` |

Pass one explicitly when you don't want the context's: `make([]int, 6, my_alloc)`.
The compiler flags `-default-to-nil-allocator` / `-default-to-panic-allocator`
(see @odin/build) catch accidental implicit allocations.

## defer

`defer stmt` runs the statement at scope exit, in LIFO order — the idiom for
pairing acquire/release:

```odin
f, err := os.open("data")
defer os.close(f)
```

## Error handling — `or_return` / `or_else`

Errors are return values, usually an enum or union as the last result. `or_return`
propagates: if the trailing value is non-zero it returns it from the enclosing
proc, zero-valuing the other named results.

```odin
load :: proc() -> (n: int, err: Error) {
    data := read_file() or_return    // returns err on failure
    parse(data)        or_return
    n = 123
    return                            // bare return uses the named results
}
```

`or_else` supplies a default for the ok-style two-value forms:
`i := m[key] or_else -1`, `v := x.(int) or_else 0`. Loop variants `or_continue` /
`or_break` accept an optional label.

## Foreign blocks (C FFI)

```odin
foreign import lib "system:Kernel32.lib"
@(default_calling_convention="std")
foreign lib {
    MessageBoxA :: proc(hwnd: rawptr, text, caption: cstring, type: u32) -> i32 ---
}
```

Calling conventions: `"odin"` (default, carries context), `"contextless"`,
`"c"`, `"stdcall"`, `"fastcall"`. Link extra libraries via
`-extra-linker-flags:` in @odin/build.
